Lifts.

A lift is a platform that rides up and down on its own, carrying the player along when they're standing on it. It runs forever, bouncing between a low point and a high point without being asked — there's no button to press and no menu to choose from. Lifts are the entity for a steady shuttle between two heights: a platform that drifts down to you, waits for you to step on by timing it, and carries you up, then comes back down for the next trip.

Lifts versus elevators versus moving platforms.

Three entities move the player vertically, and it's worth knowing which to reach for:

A lift moves up and down automatically and continuously. You ride it by timing when you step on and off — it never stops and never asks where you want to go.
An elevator is a call point with a floor menu. You stand on it, press the interact key, and pick a named floor; it takes you straight there and stops. Use an elevator when the player should choose a destination; use a lift when the motion should be constant and the timing is the challenge.
A moving platform can travel in any direction, not just up and down, and supports the snap modes for how it returns. A lift is the specialized vertical-only case that simply oscillates between its two ends. If all you want is straight up-and-down, the lift is simpler; if you need diagonal or horizontal motion, use a moving platform.

How a lift moves.

A lift travels between a minimum and a maximum height, stepping one tile at a time and waiting the speed interval between steps, then reversing when it reaches an end — so a smaller speed is a faster lift. It does this endlessly for as long as the map is loaded.

On 2d and topdown maps the vertical range is the minimum and maximum y you give it: the lift is a strip as wide as your minimum-to-maximum x, and it slides between the low y and the high y. On 3d maps you give the platform a footprint with minimum and maximum x and y, and a separate minimum and maximum z that is the height range it rides between, so the lift is a full rectangular pad that travels up and down through the z levels.

When the player is standing on the lift, they're carried with it — moving up as it rises and down as it falls. Step off at the right moment and you're left at that height; miss the timing and you ride back the other way.

Lift fields.

The lift form takes the following:

Coordinates. A minimum and maximum x and y, and on 3d maps a minimum and maximum z, defining the platform and the range it travels through as described above.

Speed. Milliseconds between each step of travel — smaller is faster.

Direction. Whether the lift starts by heading down then up, or up then down. Either way it reverses at each end and runs continuously; this only sets which way it goes first.

Tile. The surface the player stands on, exactly like a plain platform — the tile supplies the step, land, and fall sounds. Pick air for a lift with no surface sound.

Tile volume. How loud the tile's sounds play, from full down to silent.
Tile pitch. The pitch of the tile's sounds, as a flat value defaulting to 100 and ranging from 5 to 1000.

Lift sound. A continuous loop that travels with the lift so the player can hear it moving and locate it by ear — the hum of the machinery. Pick none for a silent lift.

Lift volume. How loud the lift loop plays, set separately from the tile.
Lift pitch. The pitch of the lift loop, as a flat value defaulting to 100 and ranging from 5 to 1000.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

The lift form has two sound groups. While the tile list is focused, press space to hear the tile's step clip, hold control and press L to hear its land clip, and hold control and press H to hear its fall clip. While the lift sound list is focused, press space to start or stop a looping preview of the machinery sound. The volume and pitch sliders for whichever group you're in adjust the preview live.

Authoring lifts by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a lift is: lift minx maxx miny maxy direction speed tile tilevolume tilepitch lifttype liftvolume liftpitch. On 3d maps a minimum and maximum z are inserted after the maximum y: lift minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz direction speed tile tilevolume tilepitch lifttype liftvolume liftpitch. Direction is written as a number — zero for down then up, one for up then down. The tile must match a platform tile folder name or the word air, and the lift sound must match a lift sound folder name or the word none. Volumes run from zero down to minus one hundred and pitches are a percentage around one hundred, the same as for platforms.
